                            <property name="label" translatable="yes">&lt;b&gt;Binder&lt;/b&gt; has few things are needed to know

- &lt;span color='red'&gt;&lt;b&gt;IT IS NOT REQUIRED AT ALL&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, although &lt;b&gt;BindingContract&lt;/b&gt; will do that (by default it uses Binder.&lt;b&gt;get_default&lt;/b&gt;() unless specified 
custom in its &lt;b&gt;binder&lt;/b&gt; property)
- in most all cases 1 binder is exactly what is needed and more to the fact default is already correct
- Binder can specify custom creation method for BindingInterface (by default it simply wraps &lt;b&gt;PropertyBinding.bind&lt;/b&gt;)
- you can set different default Binder with &lt;b&gt;set_default&lt;/b&gt; at application start and forget about it
- API is exactly the same as &lt;b&gt;PropertyBinding.bind&lt;/b&gt;, except in case of Binder use it will be &lt;b&gt;my_binder_reference.bind&lt;/b&gt; or 
&lt;b&gt;Binder.get_default().bind&lt;/b&gt;

&lt;b&gt;when and why use Binder?&lt;/b&gt;

- need for debugging. create new Binder instance where creation method is simply wrapped &lt;b&gt;BindingProperty.bind&lt;/b&gt; with debug output.
this combined with binders &lt;b&gt;binding_created&lt;/b&gt; signal allows tapping in whole creation
- you need custom property bindings instead of PropertyBinding, all that Binder or data binding requires is that bindings being created
are implementing &lt;b&gt;BindingInterface&lt;/b&gt;

the fact that application can tap into debugging per contract makes this extremely convenient</property>
