                                <property name="label" translatable="yes">&lt;b&gt;Property aliases (hover on label to see source)&lt;/b&gt;
&lt;small&gt;their use is simple to understand you declare specific property name and then register which property is relevant for that purpose for specific type. note
that real property name takes precedence over alias and only case when alias will be used is when original object does not contain specified property.
PropertyBinding.bind uses this by default as fallback for nonexisting properties&lt;/small&gt;

&lt;b&gt;PropertyAlias class&lt;/b&gt;
&lt;b&gt;static&lt;/b&gt; bool &lt;b&gt;contains&lt;/b&gt; (string alias) - peeks if alias exists
&lt;b&gt;static&lt;/b&gt; PropertyAlias &lt;b&gt;get_instance&lt;/b&gt; (string alias) - returns alias if exists, otherwise creates new one and returns it
PropertyAlias &lt;b&gt;register&lt;/b&gt; (Type type, string alias) - alias registration for type (returns alias group to allow API chaining)
string? &lt;b&gt;get_for&lt;/b&gt; (Type type) - returns property name for alias or null if not registered
string &lt;b&gt;safe_get_for&lt;/b&gt; (Type type, string original) - same as &lt;b&gt;get_for&lt;/b&gt; except it returns original value instead of null

&lt;small&gt;Example:
// note that "alias:" in alias name is only for readability purposes, not as requirement
PropertyAlias.get_instance ("alias:custom-name")
	.register (type(SomeType), "some-type-property")
	.register (type(OtherType), "other-type-property");

at this point binding will know what to use for "alias:custom-name" in types SomeType and OtherType which makes "alias:custom-name" valid binding
point for them&lt;/small&gt;

