                                <property name="label" translatable="yes">pointers have 2 distinct extension possibilities

- changing the way source is resolved

	Object? &lt;b&gt;redirect_to&lt;/b&gt; (&lt;span color='red'&gt;ref&lt;/span&gt; redirect_in_play) 
		&lt;i&gt;allows redirection of source and at the same time breaking the chain. example of this is &lt;b&gt;BindingPointerFromPropertyValue&lt;/b&gt;
		which resolves source it was pointed to initially and then instead of returning that object it resolves value of property
		that is specified with &lt;b&gt;data_property_name&lt;/b&gt;. the fact that it breaks the chain provides with possibility of having source
		source being pointed out of regular chain&lt;/i&gt;

- tapping into data transfer and add custom manipulation (this is only valid for pointers that specify MANUAL as their update type.

	&lt;span color='red'&gt;signal&lt;/span&gt; &lt;b&gt;data_changed&lt;/b&gt; (BindingPointer pointer, string data_change_cookie)
		&lt;i&gt;doing this allows controlling how data updates will be dispatched and also use it for any other purpose possible. one
		possible use is signal throttling where there is a need to limit amount of signals per time. example of this is
		&lt;b&gt;ThrotledManualBindingPointer&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/i&gt;</property>
